Here is the function in Julia:

```julia
function timezone_bumper(dt::DateTime; bump::Int=3)
    if !isa(dt, DateTime)
        throw(ArgumentError("Input must be of type DateTime."))
    end
    return dt .+ Dates.Hour(bump)
end
```

This function takes a DateTime object `dt` as its first argument and an integer `bump` as its second argument (with a default value of 3). If the input `dt` is not a DateTime object, it throws an ArgumentError. The function then increases the input DateTime by `bump` hours and returns the new DateTime.
